[[File:Samuel Gustaf Hermelin 1877.jpg|thumbnail|Samuel Gustaf Hermelin, 1877]] '''Samuel Gustaf Hermelin''' (4 April 1744, [[Stockholm]] – 4 March 1820) was a [[Swedish people|Swedish]] [[industrialist]], [[diplomat]] and [[cartographer]]. Samuel Gustaf also belonged to the [[Swedish nobility]]. He attended the [[University of Uppsala]] for [[mining]]. In 1782, he went to the [[United States]] to study the mining operations and served as [[List of ambassadors of Sweden to the United States| the first Swedish ambassador]] to the United States. He eventually moved back to [[Sweden]] and owned a mining company in [[Lapland (Sweden)|Lapland]].<ref name=WDL1>{{cite web|title=Map of Sweden|url=http://www.wdl.org/en/item/1225/|publisher=World Digital Library|accessdate=20 January 2013}}</ref> Samuel Gustaf was elected a Foreign Honorary Member of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]] in 1784.<ref name=AAAS>{{cite web|title=Book of Members, 1780–2010: Chapter H|url=http://www.amacad.org/publications/BookofMembers/ChapterH.pdf|publisher=American Academy of Arts and Sciences|accessdate=28 July 2014}}</ref>
